A Generalization of the Lifting Lemma for Logic Programming

Etienne Payet ‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ Fred Mesnard
Abstract

Since the seminal work of J. A. Robinson on resolution, many lifting lemmas for simplifying proofs of completeness of resolution have been proposed in the literature. In the logic programming framework, they may also help to detect some infinite derivations while proving goals under the SLD-resolution. In this paper, we first generalize a version of the lifting lemma, by extending the relation ‚Äúis more general than‚Äù so that it takes into account only some arguments of the atoms. The other arguments, which we call neutral arguments, are disregarded. Then we propose two syntactic conditions of increasing power for identifying neutral arguments from mere inspection of the text of a logic program.

1 Introduction

Since the seminal work of J. A. Robinson on resolution [16], many lifting lemmas have been proposed in the literature, see for instance [5] p. 84, [2] p. 848, [11] p. 47, [1] p. 60 or [8] where a stronger version than that of [1] is given. Lifting results are used as a tool to simplify proofs of completeness of resolution.

In this paper, we are interested in generalizing the lifting lemma presented in [1] where it is called the Lifting Theorem. Given a logic program PùëÉPitalic_P, our aim is the further design of a mechanism that generates at compile-time classes of queries that have an infinite SLD-derivation w.r.t. PùëÉPitalic_P. Towards this end, we propose a criterion in the form of a sufficient condition that enables us to identify infinite derivations.

Notice that such a condition can be easily designed from the Lifting Theorem that is proposed by Apt in [1], as we explain now. Assuming that the reader is familiar with the standard notations about logic programming reviewed in the next section, let us first recall the notion of a lift. An SLD-derivation Œæ‚Ä≤superscriptùúâ‚Ä≤\xi^{\prime}italic_Œæ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is a lift of another SLD-derivation Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ if there exists a prefix Dùê∑Ditalic_D of Œæ‚Ä≤superscriptùúâ‚Ä≤\xi^{\prime}italic_Œæ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT that is more general than Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ i.e. Dùê∑Ditalic_D is of the same length than Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ and in Dùê∑Ditalic_D and Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ the same clauses are used in the same order, atoms in the same positions are selected at each step and for each iùëñiitalic_i, the iùëñiitalic_i-th query of Dùê∑Ditalic_D is more general than that of Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ. The following result holds.

Theorem 1.1 (Lifting [1])

Let PùëÉPitalic_P be a logic program, QùëÑQitalic_Q be a query and Œ∑ùúÇ\etaitalic_Œ∑ be a substitution. For every SLD-derivation Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ of P‚à™{Q‚Å¢Œ∑}ùëÉùëÑùúÇP\cup\{Q\eta\}italic_P ‚à™ { italic_Q italic_Œ∑ }, there exists an SLD-derivation of P‚à™{Q}ùëÉùëÑP\cup\{Q\}italic_P ‚à™ { italic_Q } which is a lift of Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ.

This theorem provides a sufficient condition that can be used to identify infinite SLD-derivations.

Corollary 1

Let PùëÉPitalic_P be a logic program and Aùê¥Aitalic_A be an atom. Suppose that there exists a sequence of SLD-derivation steps from Aùê¥Aitalic_A to a query QùëÑQitalic_Q using the clauses of PùëÉPitalic_P and that QùëÑQitalic_Q contains an atom BùêµBitalic_B that is more general than Aùê¥Aitalic_A. Then there exists an infinite SLD-derivation of P‚à™{A}ùëÉùê¥P\cup\{A\}italic_P ‚à™ { italic_A }.

In this article, we extend the relation ‚Äúis more general than‚Äù so that it takes into account only some arguments of the atoms, the others (which are called neutral arguments) being, roughly, disregarded. We show that the Lifting Theorem¬†1.1, and hence Corollary¬†1, can be extended to this new relation. Neutral arguments correspond to the following intuition. Suppose we have an SLD-derivation Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ of a query QùëÑQitalic_Q w.r.t. a logic program PùëÉPitalic_P. PùëÉPitalic_P such that Œæ‚Ä≤superscriptùúâ‚Ä≤\xi^{\prime}italic_Œæ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is a lift of Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ up to the neutral arguments.

Last but not least, we offer two syntactic conditions of increasing power for easily identifying neutral arguments from mere inspection of the text of a logic program.

The paper is organized as follows. In Section¬†2, we review basic concepts concerning logic programming and introduce some notations. Then in Section¬†3 we give a generic presentation of what we mean for an argument to be neutral. In Section¬†4, we propose some particular concrete means for detecting neutral arguments. In Section¬†5, we apply our results to generate some queries that have an infinite SLD-derivation w.r.t. a given logic program. Finally, in Section¬†6 we discuss related works.

A logic program is a finite set of definite clauses. In program examples, we use the ISO-Prolog syntax. Let PùëÉPitalic_P be a logic program. 3 Neutral Arguments for SLD-Derivation

The basic idea in the work we present here relies on some arguments in clauses which we can be disregarded when unfolding a query. For instance, the second argument of the non-unit clause of the program

    append([],Ys,Ys).
    append([X|Xs],Ys,[X|Zs]) :- append(Xs,Ys,Zs).

is such a candidate. Notice that a very common programming technique called accumulator passing (see for instance e.g. [15], p. 21‚Äì25), always produces such patterns.

Example 3

A classical example of the accumulator passing technique is the following program REVERSE.

    reverse(L,R) :- rev(L,[],R).
    rev([],R,R).
    rev([X|Xs],R0,R) :- rev(Xs,[X|R0],R).

Concerning termination, we may ignore the third and the second argument of the recursive clause of rev while unfolding a query with this clause. Only the first argument can stop the unfolding. ‚àé

But we can be more precise. Instead of only identifying arguments that can be totaly disregarded as in the above examples, we can try to identify arguments that can be replaced, when unfolding a query, by any terms for which a given condition holds. Consider for instance the program

    p(x,f(z)) :- q(x,y), p(y,f(z)).

If we unfold a query p‚Å¢(t1,t2)ùëùsubscriptùë°1subscriptùë°2p(t_{1},t_{2})italic_p ( italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) with this program, then if we replace the second argument of pùëùpitalic_p by any instance t3subscriptùë°3t_{3}italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT of f‚Å¢(z)ùëìùëßf(z)italic_f ( italic_z ), we can still unfold p‚Å¢(t1,t3)ùëùsubscriptùë°1subscriptùë°3p(t_{1},t_{3})italic_p ( italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ).

In the sequel of this section, we give a technical tool to describe specific arguments inside a program and present an extension of the relation ‚Äúis more general than‚Äù. Then we formalize the concept of derivation neutrality and we propose an extended version of the Lifting Theorem¬†1.1.

3.1 Filters

Let us first introduce the notion of a filter. We use filters in order to distinguish atoms some arguments of which satisfy a given condition. A condition upon atom arguments, i.e. terms, can be defined as a mapping in the following way.

A term-condition is a mapping from T‚Å¢U‚Ñíùëásubscriptùëà‚ÑíTU_{\mathcal{L}}italic_T italic_U start_POSTSUBSCRIPT caligraphic_L end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to {ùöùùöõùöûùöé,ùöèùöäùöïùöúùöé}ùöùùöõùöûùöéùöèùöäùöïùöúùöé\{\mathtt{true},\mathtt{false}\}{ typewriter_true , typewriter_false }.

3.2 Derivation Neutral Filters: Operational Definition

Before we give a precise definition of the kind of filters we are interested in, we review the notion of a lift. The definition we propose below is the same as that of [1] p. 57 up to the arguments whose position is distinguished by a filter.

Definition 4 (Œînormal-Œî\Deltaroman_Œî-Lift)

Let ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî be a filter. Consider a sequence of SLD-derivation steps

Œæ:=Q0‚Å¢‚üπc1Q1‚Å¢‚ãØ‚Å¢Qn‚Å¢‚üπcn+1Qn+1‚Å¢‚ãØassignùúâsubscriptùëÑ0subscript‚üπsubscriptùëê1subscriptùëÑ1‚ãØsubscriptùëÑùëõsubscript‚üπsubscriptùëêùëõ1subscriptùëÑùëõ1‚ãØ\xi:=Q_{0}\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits_{c_{1}}Q_{1}\cdots Q_{n}\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits_{c_{n+1}}Q_{n+1}\cdotsitalic_Œæ := italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚üπ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_c start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚ãØ italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚üπ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_c start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n + 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n + 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚ãØ

  • ‚Ä¢

    Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ is of the same or smaller length than Œæ‚Ä≤superscriptùúâ‚Ä≤\xi^{\prime}italic_Œæ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT,

In the sequel of this paper, we focus on ‚Äúderivation neutral‚Äù filters. The name ‚Äúderivation neutral‚Äù stems from the fact that in any derivation of a query QùëÑQitalic_Q, the arguments of QùëÑQitalic_Q whose position is distinguished by such a filter can be safely replaced by any terms satisfying the associated term-condition. Such a replacement does not modify the derivation process.

Definition 5 (Derivation Neutral)

Let ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî be a filter and cùëêcitalic_c be a clause. We say that Œînormal-Œî\Deltaroman_Œî is DN for cùëêcitalic_c if

there exists a query Q1‚Ä≤subscriptsuperscriptùëÑ‚Ä≤1Q^{\prime}_{1}italic_Q start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT such that Q‚Ä≤‚Å¢‚üπcQ1‚Ä≤superscriptùëÑ‚Ä≤subscript‚üπùëêsubscriptsuperscriptùëÑ‚Ä≤1Q^{\prime}\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits_{c}Q^{\prime}_{1}italic_Q start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚üπ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_c end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Q start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and Q‚Ä≤‚Å¢‚üπcQ1‚Ä≤superscriptùëÑ‚Ä≤subscript‚üπùëêsubscriptsuperscriptùëÑ‚Ä≤1Q^{\prime}\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits_{c}Q^{\prime}_{1}italic_Q start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚üπ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_c end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Q start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is a ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî-lift of Q‚Å¢‚üπcQ1ùëÑsubscript‚üπùëêsubscriptùëÑ1Q\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits_{c}Q_{1}italic_Q ‚üπ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_c end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

This definition is extended to finite sets of clauses: Œînormal-Œî\Deltaroman_Œî is DN for a logic program PùëÉPitalic_P if it is DN for each clause of PùëÉPitalic_P.

3.3 Model Theoretic Results Induced by DN Filters

Lifting lemmas are used in the literature to prove completeness of SLD-resolution. Now that we have established an extended Lifting Theorem, it may be worth to investigate its consequences from the model theoretic point of view.

Let Eùê∏Eitalic_E be an atom or a query and ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî be a filter. Then one may ‚Äúexpand‚Äù the atoms occurring in Eùê∏Eitalic_E by replacing every argument whose position is distinguished by ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî by any term that satisfies the associated term-condition.

    where œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ denotes the empty substitution.

    Let Q:=A1,‚Ä¶,AnassignùëÑsubscriptùê¥1‚Ä¶subscriptùê¥ùëõQ:=A_{1},\dots,A_{n}italic_Q := italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚Ä¶ , italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT be a query. DN sets of positions generate DN filters.

Theorem 4.1

Let œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ be a DN set of positions for a logic program PùëÉPitalic_P. Then Œî‚Å¢[œÑ]normal-Œîdelimited-[]ùúè\Delta[\tau]roman_Œî [ italic_œÑ ] is DN for PùëÉPitalic_P.

Proposition 3

Let cùëêcitalic_c be a clause and œÑ+superscriptùúè\tau^{+}italic_œÑ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT be a set of positions with associated terms that is DN for cùëêcitalic_c. Proof

The proof of this proposition is given in Appendix 1. ‚àé

Notice that a set of positions is a particular set of positions with associated terms in the following sense.

Proposition 4

Let œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ be a set of positions and xùë•xitalic_x be any variable. Let œÑ+superscriptùúè\tau^{+}italic_œÑ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT be the set of positions with associated terms defined as: for each p‚ààŒ†ùëùnormal-Œ†p\in\Piitalic_p ‚àà roman_Œ†, œÑ+‚Å¢(p):=(œÑ‚Å¢(p)‚Ü£{x})assignsuperscriptùúèùëùnormal-‚Ü£ùúèùëùùë•\tau^{+}(p):=(\;\tau(p)\rightarrowtail\{x\}\;)italic_œÑ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_p ) := ( italic_œÑ ( italic_p ) ‚Ü£ { italic_x } ). Then, the following holds.

  1. 1.

    An atom Aùê¥Aitalic_A is Œî‚Å¢[œÑ]Œîdelimited-[]ùúè\Delta[\tau]roman_Œî [ italic_œÑ ]-more general than an atom BùêµBitalic_B iff Aùê¥Aitalic_A is Œî‚Å¢[œÑ+]Œîdelimited-[]superscriptùúè\Delta[\tau^{+}]roman_Œî [ italic_œÑ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ]-more general than BùêµBitalic_B.

  2. 2.

    For any clause cùëêcitalic_c, œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ is DN for cùëêcitalic_c iff œÑ+superscriptùúè\tau^{+}italic_œÑ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is DN for cùëêcitalic_c.

Proof

The proof follows from these remarks.

  • ‚Ä¢

    Item¬†1 is a direct consequence of the definition of ‚ÄúŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî-more general‚Äù (see Definition¬†3) and the definition of the filter associated to a set of positions (see Definition¬†9) and to a set of positions with associated terms (see Definition¬†12).

  • ‚Ä¢

    Item¬†2 is a direct consequence of the definition of DN sets of positions (see Definition¬†10), and DN sets of positions with associated terms (see Definition¬†13). ‚àé

Finally, the sets of positions with associated terms of Definition¬†13 were named after ‚ÄúDN‚Äù because of the following result.

5 Examples

In this section, we focus on left derivations i.e. we only consider the leftmost selection rule: Q‚Å¢‚üπQ‚Ä≤ùëÑ‚üπsuperscriptùëÑ‚Ä≤Q\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits Q^{\prime}italic_Q ‚üπ italic_Q start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is a left derivation step if it is an SLD-derivation step whose selected atom is the first atom of QùëÑQitalic_Q from the left. We say that a query QùëÑQitalic_Q left loops w.r.t. a program PùëÉPitalic_P if there exists an infinite left derivation of P‚à™{Q}ùëÉùëÑP\cup\{Q\}italic_P ‚à™ { italic_Q }. Notice that the ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî-Lifting Theorem¬†3.1 provides a sufficient condition to identify left loops as it generates the following corollary.

Corollary 2 (from Theorem¬†3.1)

Let PùëÉPitalic_P be a logic program and Œînormal-Œî\Deltaroman_Œî be a DN filter for PùëÉPitalic_P. If A‚Å¢‚üπP*B1,ùêÅ1ùê¥subscriptsuperscriptnormal-‚üπùëÉsubscriptùêµ1subscriptùêÅ1A\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits^{*}_{P}B_{1},\textup{\bf B}_{1}italic_A ‚üπ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT * end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_P end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and B1‚Å¢‚üπP+B2,ùêÅ2subscriptùêµ1subscriptsuperscriptnormal-‚üπùëÉsubscriptùêµ2subscriptùêÅ2B_{1}\mathop{\Longrightarrow}\limits^{+}_{P}B_{2},\textup{\bf B}_{2}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚üπ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_P end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and B2subscriptùêµ2B_{2}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is Œînormal-Œî\Deltaroman_Œî-more general than B1subscriptùêµ1B_{1}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT then P‚à™{A}ùëÉùê¥P\cup\{A\}italic_P ‚à™ { italic_A } left loops.

Proof

The proof is similar to that of Corollary¬†1.

This section presents some examples of atomic queries that have an infinite left derivation w.r.t. a given logic program. We use Corollary¬†2 with DN sets of positions and DN sets of positions with associated terms. In each case, it is not possible to conclude using the classical Lifting Theorem¬†1.1. The last example exhibits a case where we are not able conclude.

6 Related Works

Some extensions of the Lifting Theorem with respect to infinite derivations are presented in [9], where the authors study numerous properties of finite failure. The non-ground finite failure set of a logic program is defined as the set of possibly non-ground atoms which admit a fair finitely failed SLD-tree w.r.t. the program. This denotation is shown correct in the following sense. If two programs have the same non-ground finite failure set, then any ground or non-ground goal which finitely fails w.r.t. one program also finitely fails w.r.t. the other. Such a property is false when we consider the standard ground finite failure set. The proof of correctness of the non-ground finite failure semantics relies on the following result. First, a derivation is called non-perpetual if it is a fair infinite derivation and there exists a finite depth from which unfolding does not instantiate the original goal any more. Then the authors define the definite answer goal of a non-perpetual derivation as the maximal instantiation of the original goal. A crucial lemma states that any instance of the definite answer goal admits a similar non-perpetual derivation. Compared to our work, note that we do need fairness as an hypothesis for the ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî-Lifting Theorem¬†3.1. On the other hand, investigating the relationships between non-ground arguments of definite answer and neutral arguments is an interesting problem.

Loop checking in logic programming is also a subject related to our work. In this area, [4] sets up some solid foundations. A loop check is a device to prune derivations when it seems appropriate. A loop checker is defined as sound if no solution is lost. It is complete if all infinite derivations are pruned. A complete loop check may also prune finite derivations. The authors shows that even for function-free programs (also known as Datalog programs), sound and complete loop checks are out of reach. Completeness is shown only for some restricted classes of function-free programs.

We now review loop checking in more details. To our best knowledge, among all existing loop checking mechanisms only OS-check [17], EVA-check [19] and VAF-check [20] are suitable for logic programs with function symbols. They rely on a structural characteristic of infinite SLD-derivations, namely, the growth of the size of some generated subgoals. This is what the following theorem states.

Theorem 6.1

Consider an infinite SLD-derivation Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ where the leftmost selection rule is used. Then there are infinitely many queries Qi1subscriptùëÑsubscriptùëñ1Q_{i_{1}}italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, Qi2subscriptùëÑsubscriptùëñ2Q_{i_{2}}italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, ‚Ä¶ (with i1<i2<‚Ä¶subscriptùëñ1subscriptùëñ2italic-‚Ä¶i_{1}<i_{2}<\dotsitalic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT < italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT < italic_‚Ä¶) in Œæùúâ\xiitalic_Œæ such that for any j‚â•1ùëó1j\geq 1italic_j ‚â• 1, the selected atom Aijsubscriptùê¥subscriptùëñùëóA_{i_{j}}italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT of QijsubscriptùëÑsubscriptùëñùëóQ_{i_{j}}italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is an ancestor of the selected atom Aij+1subscriptùê¥subscriptùëñùëó1A_{i_{j+1}}italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j + 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT of Qij+1subscriptùëÑsubscriptùëñùëó1Q_{i_{j+1}}italic_Q start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j + 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(Aij+1)‚â•ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(Aij)ùë†ùëñùëßùëísubscriptùê¥subscriptùëñùëó1ùë†ùëñùëßùëísubscriptùê¥subscriptùëñùëó\mathit{size}(A_{i_{j+1}})\geq\mathit{size}(A_{i_{j}})italic_size ( italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j + 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ‚â• italic_size ( italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ).

Here, ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùë†ùëñùëßùëí\mathit{size}italic_size is a given function that maps an atom to its size which is defined in terms of the number of symbols appearing in the atom. As this theorem does not provide any sufficient condition to detect infinite SLD-derivations, the three loop checking mechanisms mentioned above may detect finite derivations as infinite. However, these mechanisms are complete w.r.t. the leftmost selection rule i.e. they detect all infinite loops when the leftmost selection rule is used.

OS-check (for OverSize loop check) was first introduced by Shalin [17, 18] and was then formalized by Bol [3]. It is based on a function ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùë†ùëñùëßùëí\mathit{size}italic_size that can have one of the three following definitions: for any atoms Aùê¥Aitalic_A and BùêµBitalic_B, either ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(A)=ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(B)ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùê¥ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùêµ\mathit{size}(A)=\mathit{size}(B)italic_size ( italic_A ) = italic_size ( italic_B ), either ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(A)ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùê¥\mathit{size}(A)italic_size ( italic_A ) (resp. ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(B)ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùêµ\mathit{size}(B)italic_size ( italic_B )) is the count of symbols appearing in Aùê¥Aitalic_A (resp. BùêµBitalic_B), either ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(A)‚â§ùë†ùëñùëßùëí‚Å¢(B)ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùê¥ùë†ùëñùëßùëíùêµ\mathit{size}(A)\leq\mathit{size}(B)italic_size ( italic_A ) ‚â§ italic_size ( italic_B ) if for each iùëñiitalic_i, the count of symbols of the iùëñiitalic_i-th argument of Aùê¥Aitalic_A is smaller than or equal to that of the iùëñiitalic_i-th argument of BùêµBitalic_B. OS-check says that an SLD-derivation may be infinite if it generates an atomic subgoal Aùê¥Aitalic_A that is oversized, i.e. that has ancestor subgoals which have the same predicate symbol as Aùê¥Aitalic_A and whose size is smaller than or equal to that of Aùê¥Aitalic_A.

EVA-check (for Extented Variant Atoms loop check) was introduced by Shen [19]. It is based on the notion of generalized variants. EVA-check says that an SLD-derivation may be infinite if it generates an atomic subgoal Aùê¥Aitalic_A that is a generalized variant of some of its ancestor A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, i.e. Aùê¥Aitalic_A is a variant of A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT except for some arguments whose size increases from A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT to Aùê¥Aitalic_A via a set of recursive clauses. Here the size function that is used applies to predicate arguments, i.e. to terms, and it is fixed: it is defined as the the count of symbols that appear in the terms. EVA-check is more reliable than OS-check because it is less likely to mis-identify infinite loops [19]. This is mainly due to the fact that, unlike OS-check, EVA-check refers to the informative internal structure of subgoals.

VAF-check (for Variant Atoms loop check for logic programs with Functions) was proposed by Shen et al. [20]. It is based on the notion of expanded variants. VAF-check says that an SLD-derivation may be infinite if it generates an atomic subgoal Aùê¥Aitalic_A that is an expanded variant of some of its ancestor A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, i.e. Aùê¥Aitalic_A is a variant of A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT except for some arguments ti1,‚Ä¶,tinsubscriptùë°subscriptùëñ1‚Ä¶subscriptùë°subscriptùëñùëõt_{i_{1}},\dots,t_{i_{n}}italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚Ä¶ , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT such that: ti1subscriptùë°subscriptùëñ1t_{i_{1}}italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT grows from A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT to Aùê¥Aitalic_A into a function containing ti1subscriptùë°subscriptùëñ1t_{i_{1}}italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, ‚Ä¶, tinsubscriptùë°subscriptùëñùëõt_{i_{n}}italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT grows from A‚Ä≤superscriptùê¥‚Ä≤A^{\prime}italic_A start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT to Aùê¥Aitalic_A into a function containing tinsubscriptùë°subscriptùëñùëõt_{i_{n}}italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. VAF-check is as reliable as and more efficient than EVA-check [20].

The main difference with our work is that we want to pinpoint some infinite derivations, based on syntactical properties of the program. We are not interested in completeness nor in soundness. Notice, however, that using the ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî-Lifting Theorem¬†3.1 as a loop checker leads to a device that is neither complete (see Example¬†17) nor sound since the Lifting Theorem¬†1.1 is a particular case of the ŒîŒî\Deltaroman_Œî-Lifting Theorem¬†3.1.

7 Conclusion

We have presented a generalization of the lifting lemma for logic programming, which allows to disregard some arguments, termed neutral arguments, while checking for subsumption. We have investigated the model theoretic consequence of this generalization and have proposed two syntactic criteria for statically identifying neutral arguments.

A first application of this work has already been presented in [14], in the area of termination analysis of logic programs. We combine cTI [13], a termination inference tool with a non-termination inference analyzer whose correctness relies on our generalized lifting lemma. The resulting combined analysis may sometimes characterize the termination behavior of some concrete logic program w.r.t. to the left selection rule and the language we use to describe classes of queries.

Finally, this paper leaves numerous questions open. For instance, it might be interesting to try to generalize this approach to constraint logic programming [10]. Can we obtain higher level proofs compared to those we give? Can we propose more abstract or semantically-based criteria for identifying neutral arguments?

Acknowledgements. We thank Ulrich Neumerkel for initial discussions on this topic and Roberto Bagnara for interesting suggestions.

Proposition 7 (One Step Œînormal-Œî\Deltaroman_Œî-Lifting)
